2) Set Git line-ending behavior (recommended for Windows)
```powershell
git config --global core.autocrlf true
```

3) Remove node_modules from the repo index (do NOT delete local files)
```powershell
cd "D:\Projects\Interactive Dashboard"
git rm -r --cached node_modules
git add .gitignore
git commit -m "Remove node_modules from repo and add .gitignore"
git push origin main
```

4) Verify node_modules no longer tracked and repo size reduced
```powershell
git ls-files | Select-String "node_modules" -SimpleMatch     # should show nothing
git rev-list --objects --all --count
```

5) If you already pushed large history and need to purge node_modules from history (optional / more intrusive)
- Install BFG locally and run (be careful; this rewrites history and requires force-push):
```powershell
# example using BFG (do on a local clone)
git clone --mirror https://github.com/YOUR_USER/Interactive-Dashboard.git
java -jar bfg.jar --delete-folders node_modules --delete-files package-lock.json Interactive-Dashboard.git
cd Interactive-Dashboard.git
git reflog expire --expire=now --all
git gc --prune=now --aggressive
git push --force
```
(Only do this if you understand history rewrite and collaborators.)

6) Rebuild image and push workflow (optional after repo cleaned)
```powershell
# ensure package-lock and package.json are present and node_modules not in git
docker compose build --no-cache web
docker compose up -d
```

